Comment: I liked this variant but it should not be called Fibonacci sequence since by definition it is defined as sum of previous two numbers.

Comment: I came up with my own solution in C#, then looked at author's (shorter) and was able to successfully adapt it to C#.  This was my first time working with a Fibonacci sequence, so it took me longer, but it seems doable within 5 minutes.  Author is receptive to feedback and has implemented suggestions from other users.

Just a quick spell check:
In your input description "Line 2: An integer order for the number of previous numbers you need to calculate the sum off", the word 'off' should be 'of'.

Would "count" sound better instead of "order"?

"A Fibonacci sequence of [count] n is an integer sequence where each element is the sum of the previous n elements, except for the first n elements which are 0."
"Line 2: An integer [count] being the number of previous integers you need to calculate the sum of"

Just a thought.

I came up with my own solution in C#, then looked at yours (shorter) and was able to successfully adapt it to C#.  This was my first time working with a Fibonacci sequence, so it took me longer, but it seems doable within 5 minutes.

I thought this was a good puzzle and would be willing to approve it after fixing the spelling mistake.
I hope you received enough feedback from the community to improve your contribution. Once you have made the necessary updates, publish your contribution!
A way to solve it in Python in 100 characters...

There are typos in the name. It is not Fibbonanci but Fibonacci.
Correct that and I will valid the challenge. Because me I like this kind of computation.

Maybe you can also replace the "key" mention by "order":
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generalizations_of_Fibonacci_numbers#Fibonacci_numbers_of_higher_order

Also maybe add the following constraint: key ≤ numbers. Else there are special cases not checked by your test cases.
Good Idea! But it is probably to hard for Reverse Mode.

By the way I just proposed this challenge:
"Divisibility of Fibonacci numbers sum"
https://www.codingame.com/contribute/view/6071bfe55e7b9857ce7570364b83c34ed4fe

n=int(input())
o=int(input())
s=[0]*(o-1)+[1]
for _ in ' '*(n-o):s+=[sum(s[-o:])]
print(*s,sep=', ')

Another comment in this contribution shows the link: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generalizations_of_Fibonacci_numbers#Fibonacci_numbers_of_higher_order
Over here it said that the order variable should be named order.

I fixed the other mistake.
